queer beast, Jim. They ain&rsquo;t dried fish, and they never grew on stalk or vine. I&rsquo;m afraid of &lsquo;em. Anyhow, I should n&rsquo;t want to eat anything that had been shut up for months with old clothes and goose pillows.&rdquo;
She threw the package into the stove, but I bit off a corner of one of the chips I held in my hand, and chewed it tentatively. I never forgot the strange taste; though it was many years before I knew that those little brown shavings, which the Shimerdas had brought so far and treasured so jealously, were dried mushrooms. They had been gathered, probably, in some deep Bohemian forest &hellip; . . .
